---
import TopNav from "../components/TopNav.astro";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <title>How Vote Labels Work | NH Deserves Better</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="How NH Deserves Better interprets yea, nay, ITL, support, opposition, and testimony alignment vote labels."
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <TopNav />
    <main class="page">
      <a class="back" href="/">Back home</a>

      <section class="hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p>
        <h1>How Vote Labels Work</h1>
        <p>
          A recorded vote is not always as simple as “yea means support” and
          “nay means oppose.” The meaning depends on the motion being voted on.
          Vote labels translate the raw vote into the position that vote had on
          the bill.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="panel">
        <h2>Raw Vote First</h2>
        <p>
          Vote cards show the actual recorded vote first, such as Yea, Nay,
          Absent, or Present not voting. Then they explain what that vote meant
          in context.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="grid">
        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Regular Passage Motions</h2>
          <p>
            For ordinary passage motions, a yea vote is generally treated as
            support for the bill and a nay vote is generally treated as
            opposition to the bill.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>ITL and Kill Motions</h2>
          <p>
            Some motions are about stopping a bill, such as Inexpedient to
            Legislate, often abbreviated ITL. In those cases, a yea vote usually
            opposes the bill, while a nay vote usually supports keeping the bill
            alive.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Tracked Bills</h2>
          <p>
            When a bill is in the bill tracker, the tracker can provide specific
            yea and nay interpretations. Those are used when available because
            they are more precise than a general rule.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
          <h2>Testimony Alignment</h2>
          <p>
            When testimony data is available, vote cards compare the inferred
            vote position with the public testimony position. That is why a card
            might say “Nay: Support - aligned with testimony position.”
          </p>
        </article>
      </section>

      <section class="panel note">
        <h2>Why Labels May Change</h2>
        <p>
          Vote labels can improve as bill tracker data, testimony data, and roll
          call details become more complete. The raw recorded vote is preserved
          so visitors can always see the underlying action.
        </p>
        <a href="/vote-grades">How letter grades work</a>
      </section>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>
  :global(body) {
    margin: 0;
    font-family:
      Inter, ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI",
      sans-serif;
    background: #f7f4ee;
    color: #1f2933;
  }

  .page {
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 40px 0 72px;
    width: min(1040px, calc(100% - 32px));
  }

  .back,
  a {
    color: #1f2933;
    font-weight: 900;
  }

  .hero {
    padding: 28px 0 18px;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    color: #6b4f2a;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 950;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.45rem, 7vw, 4.8rem);
    line-height: 0.95;
    margin: 0 0 18px;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    margin: 0 0 10px;
  }

  p {
    color: #4b5563;
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .hero p {
    font-size: 1.08rem;
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  .grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 16px;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  .panel {
    background: white;
    border: 2px solid #1f2933;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #1f2933;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .note {
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  .note a {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 14px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
